Package: picam-orchestrator
Architecture: arm64
Depends: ${shlibs:Depends}, ${misc:Depends}, picam-raw, picam-hailo
Description: WebRTC (VP8) stream + camera control backend for picam-raw + picam-hailo (Go)
 Headless backend exposing Main / Lores live video over WebRTC (VP8,
 real inter-frame video). WHEP-style signaling at
 POST /webrtc/offer?stream=main|lores (SDP offer in, SDP answer out),
 plus a JSON status endpoint (/status.json), an on-the-fly OSD toggle
 (/osd), a per-resolution annotation toggle (/annotate), and a
 camera-switch proxy to picam-raw (/camera?id=N). No web interface of
 its own, and never talks to a browser directly — picam-frontend is
 the only client, relaying both signaling and media on to browsers.
 Each connected client selects its stream independently. Main and
 Lores are live feeds straight from picam-raw; either can be switched
 into a delayed+annotated mode that matches detections from
 picam-hailo by timestamp and draws bounding boxes onto the delayed
 frames. Also drives picam-recorder on detection activity and writes
 JSON event-log files alongside recordings. Event snapshot files saved
 to disk are plain JPEG.
 .
 This is a from-scratch Go reimplementation of the original C++
 picam-orchestrator, with the same wire protocols, config file, and
 HTTP/TCP endpoints — see its README for the full behavioral spec.
 WebRTC is provided by the pure-Go pion/webrtc (no vendored
 libdatachannel/OpenSSL build step); VP8 encoding uses cgo bindings to
 the system libvpx.
 .
 Install picam-frontend on one machine to get a browser UI that can
 view, switch streams/cameras, and toggle the OSD across multiple
 picam-orchestrator backends (e.g. several Pis) from one page.
 .
 Config: /etc/picam-orchestrator/config.ini
